# Rendering Pipeline

Viberanium renders with **WebGPU only** (`GpuDevice`). There is no WebGL2/GLSL path.

## Pass Order (per frame)

```
Shadow pass          â†’ depth shadow map
Forward pass         â†’ MSAA scene targets (lit + skinned + ground + instanced props)
MSAA resolve         â†’ scene color texture
Post-process chain   â†’ ping-pong â†’ canvas
```

Compute (when enabled) runs before/alongside draw prep:
- skeletal pose / skin palette / attachments
- static prop cull â†’ indirect draws
- collision resolve (optional; compact root readback only)

## Post-Process Chain

Stages execute in insertion order via `RenderPipeline.addPostProcess(stage)`.
Each stage receives the previous stage's output texture view; the last writes to the canvas.

```typescript
const myStage: PostProcessStage = {
  name: 'bloom',
  enabled: true,
  draw: (inputView, w, h, outputView) => bloomPass.draw(inputView, w, h, outputView),
};
pipeline.addPostProcess(myStage);
```

Built-in engine stage:
1. `tone-color` â€” ACES tone-map + warm grade + cheap bloom (always on)

Optional stages (registered by the game):
- `ascii` â€” via `createAsciiPostProcessStage(device)`; game owns toggle input

## Adding a New Pass

- Create `viberanium/src/render/passes/myPass.ts` â€” factory returning `draw` / `destroy`
- Create WGSL in `viberanium/src/render/shaders/myWgsl.ts` and wire via the pass factory or `pipeline.addPostProcess`
- Games register optional stages from `bootstrap.ts`

## Shader Conventions

- Shader modules export only WGSL strings (`/* wgsl */` template literals, no runtime logic)
- Shared WGSL snippets are imported as const strings and interpolated into larger modules
- `fullscreenPostWGSL` in `shaders/postWgsl.ts` is the canonical full-screen triangle VS â€” reuse it for post passes
- Joint palettes and large arrays use **storage buffers**, not uniform arrays

## Draw collection

The render pipeline collects draw items from:

1. `meshDraws.parts[]` on any entity (skeletal characters, bone-attachment children)
2. `renderable` on simple entities (gizmos, overlays, non-batched props)
3. `groundPlane` on the scene ground entity (dedicated ground shader)
4. `staticPropBatcher` prepared batches (opaque static props â†’ instanced / indirect draws)

Each `MeshDrawPart` supplies `mesh`, `material`, `model` (world matrix), optional `skin`, and `visible`/`castShadow` flags. GPU pose writes joint palettes and attachment models without CPU joint readback.

Runtime visibility: set `part.visible = false` or `renderable.visible = false`. Runtime material swap: replace `part.material` or `material.baseColorTex`.

Draw collection applies distance cull (`forwardCullDist` / `shadowCullDist`) and CPU sphere-vs-frustum cull for non-batched draws. Batched props use compute frustum/distance cull. Camera frustum cull only skips the forward pass. Shadow casters are culled against the light frustum (and `shadowCullDist`). Backface culling is on by default; set `material.doubleSided = true` (or glTF `doubleSided`) to disable it per draw. Ground draws always disable cull.

Opaque non-batched items are sorted by material/mesh affinity. Transparent items are sorted back-to-front by camera distance.

## Sync rules

- Skinning / bone attachments: GPU-only between compute pose and draw
- Character bodies: CPU broadphase + cylinder resolve, or optional GPU resolve with compact root SoA readback only
- Never require per-frame full joint-tree readback for rendering
